    {
      "id": "cOChdJYQXUuqXlxppGcNA",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2945.047480041853,
      "y": 642.2364533236376,
      "width": 1187.1390380859375,
      "height": 1150,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b8T",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1253206944,
      "version": 2736,
      "versionNonce": 108587616,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771726929083,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dives\n\n*scaling server for high QPS => even if can we dont want a single point of failure\n\nDeep Dives 1: scaling WS servers\nScale WebSocket servers (scaling stateful servers)\nlayer 4 load balancer\n1. client makes tcp connection with LB, then LB makes symmetric TCP conn with WS server\n    * gonna be as if client is directly connecting to WS server\n    * LB can decide which WS server client connects to\n2. LB will choose least conns\n3. LB will also route conns with new servers / re-route conns for server that was removed\n4. **PROB** clients are now on differ servers => routing prob\n\nsoln1:\nkafka\n1. kafka topic is set up for each user\n2. when user connects, it subscribes to topic\n3. any new message intended for that user will be published to that topic\n\n* bad because kafka isnt architected for billions of topics\n* consumes alot of MEM ~100kB per topic, overhead, (logging, retention buffering etc.)\n* not built for rapid connects & disconnects (coz users arent always online)\n\nsoln2:\nredis pub sub\nat most 1 guarantee => we have guarantee delivery already\n* hard to scale => same issue as having multiple servers anws\n*bad is that it doesnt guarantee delivery of msg\n\nsoln3:\nconsistent hashring\n* chat registry is for clients to query directly\n* zookeeper is for chat servers to query directly\n1. when clientA wants to send a message, it will first find out which server its suppose to connect to\n2. it then makes the connection to that chat server\n3. after writing the message, chat server then wants to broad cast the message to participants\n4. chat server will then use the configs from zookeeper to find the correct servers for that & forward to those servers\n5. the receiving server will then check if that user is connected via its own internal hashmap, & then send the msg if it it\n\n*2 hops instead of singular server\n* scaling becomes orchestration, 4 -> 5, users need to be moved\n    zookeeper will have push notifications that a server will be disconnected soon\n    then servers will be slowly trying to reconnect different users to active servers\n    no thunder disconnects\n* sometimes also encounter hot key issues (disproportionate amt of connections)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dives\n\n*scaling server for high QPS => even if can we dont want a single point of failure\n\nDeep Dives 1: scaling WS servers\nScale WebSocket servers (scaling stateful servers)\nlayer 4 load balancer\n1. client makes tcp connection with LB, then LB makes symmetric TCP conn with WS server\n    * gonna be as if client is directly connecting to WS server\n    * LB can decide which WS server client connects to\n2. LB will choose least conns\n3. LB will also route conns with new servers / re-route conns for server that was removed\n4. **PROB** clients are now on differ servers => routing prob\n\nsoln1:\nkafka\n1. kafka topic is set up for each user\n2. when user connects, it subscribes to topic\n3. any new message intended for that user will be published to that topic\n\n* bad because kafka isnt architected for billions of topics\n* consumes alot of MEM ~100kB per topic, overhead, (logging, retention buffering etc.)\n* not built for rapid connects & disconnects (coz users arent always online)\n\nsoln2:\nredis pub sub\nat most 1 guarantee => we have guarantee delivery already\n* hard to scale => same issue as having multiple servers anws\n*bad is that it doesnt guarantee delivery of msg\n\nsoln3:\nconsistent hashring\n* chat registry is for clients to query directly\n* zookeeper is for chat servers to query directly\n1. when clientA wants to send a message, it will first find out which server its suppose to connect to\n2. it then makes the connection to that chat server\n3. after writing the message, chat server then wants to broad cast the message to participants\n4. chat server will then use the configs from zookeeper to find the correct servers for that & forward to those servers\n5. the receiving server will then check if that user is connected via its own internal hashmap, & then send the msg if it it\n\n*2 hops instead of singular server\n* scaling becomes orchestration, 4 -> 5, users need to be moved\n    zookeeper will have push notifications that a server will be disconnected soon\n    then servers will be slowly trying to reconnect different users to active servers\n    no thunder disconnects\n* sometimes also encounter hot key issues (disproportionate amt of connections)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
