    {
      "id": "jwtddfiX-12WQW96WRV2p",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2943.5199063309988,
      "y": 1859.3569083346006,
      "width": 1215.139404296875,
      "height": 425,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9i",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 339421088,
      "version": 593,
      "versionNonce": 1717127072,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771731161921,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dive 3: Multiple devices\nwant to include a client table\n\nClient\n    userId              <----1 user has multiple clients (devices)\n    clientId\n\n- each device is 1 client\n- then in your chat participants,\n- for each participant, look up the clients that will receive this message\n- then update the inbox for EVERY client\n(now its # client * inbox)\n\nbad:\n- more QPS\n- now will have multiple updates on the inbox table, might need to change group size (dynamoDB only can update ~100 rows)\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dive 3: Multiple devices\nwant to include a client table\n\nClient\n    userId              <----1 user has multiple clients (devices)\n    clientId\n\n- each device is 1 client\n- then in your chat participants,\n- for each participant, look up the clients that will receive this message\n- then update the inbox for EVERY client\n(now its # client * inbox)\n\nbad:\n- more QPS\n- now will have multiple updates on the inbox table, might need to change group size (dynamoDB only can update ~100 rows)\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "gB4BBW24NwoQulmFKYuKb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 4229.572270517045,
      "y": 1717.9481293394576,
      "width": 950.75927734375,
      "height": 450,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9j",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1928935008,
      "version": 937,
      "versionNonce": 1710098016,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771733103254,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dive 4: Clean up service\n\n- intro clean up service\n- have an index on the timestamp\n\n* if we dont need to store messages forever,\n=> when client receives msg & ack-ed, we delete from the DB also\n    and not just the inbox table\n=> need to add timestamp to inbox & index it, so that we can lookup & delete those messages\n\n*race conditions => might cause this to miss some msgs, but we do have 30 days for clean up\n                     => will eventually get cleaned up\n\n- for media cleanup,\n=> S3 doesnt have a per object TTL\n=> but u can set lifecycle rules which allows u to delete objects after T time in a specific bucket\n=> its more like a cron job that checks periodically rather than a proactive TTL expiry\n=> can set this to delete objs after 30 days so that it wil clean up",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dive 4: Clean up service\n\n- intro clean up service\n- have an index on the timestamp\n\n* if we dont need to store messages forever,\n=> when client receives msg & ack-ed, we delete from the DB also\n    and not just the inbox table\n=> need to add timestamp to inbox & index it, so that we can lookup & delete those messages\n\n*race conditions => might cause this to miss some msgs, but we do have 30 days for clean up\n                     => will eventually get cleaned up\n\n- for media cleanup,\n=> S3 doesnt have a per object TTL\n=> but u can set lifecycle rules which allows u to delete objects after T time in a specific bucket\n=> its more like a cron job that checks periodically rather than a proactive TTL expiry\n=> can set this to delete objs after 30 days so that it wil clean up",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
  ],
